🧠 First: What is a Double?

A double is a fake object.

It’s used when:

You don’t want to use a real object, but you need something that behaves like it.

Think of it like a stand-in actor in a movie.

1️⃣ Basic double
Definition

A double is a completely fake object.

It does NOT check whether methods actually exist on real classes.

Example
payment_gateway = double("PaymentGateway")

Now this is just a fake object.

It doesn’t know anything.

You can define behavior:

allow(payment_gateway).to receive(:charge).and_return("Success")

Now:

payment_gateway.charge(100)

returns "Success".

Even if the real PaymentGateway class doesn’t have charge.

⚠️ That’s important.

🚨 Problem with normal double

If you write:

allow(payment_gateway).to receive(:wrong_method)

RSpec will allow it.

Even if the real class doesn’t have that method.

This can hide bugs.

2️⃣ instance_double

Now we level up.

Definition

instance_double verifies against a real class.

It checks:

Does this method actually exist on instances of this class?

Example

Suppose you have:

class PaymentGateway
  def charge(amount)
    "Charged #{amount}"
  end
end

Now:

gateway = instance_double(PaymentGateway)

Now this double knows:

It represents an instance of PaymentGateway.

If you write:

allow(gateway).to receive(:charge).and_return("Success")

✅ Works (because method exists).

If you write:

allow(gateway).to receive(:refund)

❌ Fails immediately.

Because refund does not exist on real class.

🔥 Why This Is Powerful

It prevents:

Typos

Refactoring bugs

Calling non-existing methods

This is called a verifying double.

3️⃣ class_double

Now instead of faking an instance…

We fake the class itself.

Definition

class_double verifies class methods.

Example:

class PaymentGateway
  def self.charge(amount)
    "Charged #{amount}"
  end
end

Now:

gateway_class = class_double(PaymentGateway)

If you write:

allow(gateway_class).to receive(:charge).and_return("Success")

✅ Works.

If you write:

allow(gateway_class).to receive(:wrong_method)

❌ Fails.

Because class doesn’t have that method.

🧠 Clean Comparison Table

| Type            | What it fakes     | Verifies real methods? |
| --------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------- |
| double          | Anything          | ❌ No                   |
| instance_double | Instance of class | ✅ Yes                  |
| class_double    | Class methods     | ✅ Yes                  |

🔥 Real-World Example (Service Object)

Suppose:

class PaymentProcessor
  def call(amount)
    PaymentGateway.charge(amount)
  end
end

Test:

gateway = class_double(PaymentGateway)
allow(gateway).to receive(:charge).and_return("Success")

stub_const("PaymentGateway", gateway)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(100)

Now:

No real API

Verified method existence

Safe and clean

🎯 Interview-Ready Definitions
Double

A fake object with no verification against a real class.

Instance Double

A verifying double that ensures stubbed methods exist on instances of a real class.

Class Double

A verifying double that ensures stubbed methods exist as class methods on a real class.

